{
  "answer": "**The Bṛhaspati Smṛti (Chapter 1)** anatomizes the court of justice (*dharmādhikaraṇa*) as a \"ten-limbed instrument\" (*daśāṅga*), presided over by the king.[^1][^2]\n\nThe verse listing the specific limbs mentioned—king as head, appointed judicial officer (*prāḍvivāka*) as mouth, assessors (*sabhāsthāyinaḥ*) as arms, Smṛti as hands, and accountant (*lekhaka*) and scribe (*kāyastha*) together as shanks—is as follows:\n\n> Of these limbs, the king is the head, and the appointed officer is called the mouth;  \n> the assessors are the arms, the Smṛti the hands, and the accountant and scribe the shanks. // Brh_1,1.84 //\n\nThe remaining limbs (eyes: gold, fire, water; heart: king's conscience; feet: his own officer) follow immediately in the next verse.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-a30c28).\n\n[^2]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-508073).\n\n[^3]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-db3b97).",
